<HEAD>`National Geographic Explorer' Traces Hunt for Sunken German Warship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riding the waves, the Bismarck plowed across
the seas as the fiercest fighting ship in World War II. Collapsed
on the ocean floor, the German battleship looks cowed, a beaten
Nazi relic.
   The 1941 sinking of the Bismarck _ and this year's discovery of
its eerily well-preserved wreckage _ is the subject of ``National
Geographic Explorer,'' airing on cable's TBS on Oct. 29 at 9 p.m.
EST.
   The host of the one-hour special is Robert Ballard, the
oceanographer who previously discovered the remains of the Titanic.
The 1987 television account of the Titanic find still stands as
basic cable's most popular show.
   ``The Bismarck initially was just another hunt, just another
ship,'' Ballard said. ``But when I saw the faded remains of the
swastika on the ship's bow and stern, and a solitary seaman's boot
lying on the ocean floor, that symbolized to me the great tragedy
of World War II.''
   Ballard's Bismarck show will repeat Oct. 30 at midnight EST and
Nov. 4 at 8 a.m. EST. A videocassette of the program will be
released in December by National Geographic, whose November
magazine also details the Bismarck exploration.
   The Bismarck was the most formidable battleship of its era. In
its first tour of duty, the 820-foot floating fortress literally
blew Britain's prize battle cruiser Hood out of the water, killing
all but three of the Hood's 1,419-person crew.
   ``At the time, it was the most powerful ship on the sea,'' Peter
Schnall, co-producer of the Bismarck documentary, said of the
German warship. ``It threatened to stop basically all of the supply
ships that were coming in through the North Atlantic to England.''
   A terrorized Britain put every available warship into the
1,750-mile chase after the Bismarck. Prime Minister Winston
Churchill made his orders to his navy perfectly clear: ``Sink the
Bismarck!''
   Two days after destroying the Hood and racing for protection,
the Bismarck was crippled by a British torpedo-equipped biplane and
the country's carrier Ark Royal. The combined assault ruined the
Bismarck's steering gear and rudders.
   Functionally immobile, the warship was bombarded all night and
finally scuttled by the Germans. Only 115 of the Bismarck's 2,200
hands survived.
   ``The Germans put everything into'' the battleship, Schnall
said. ``But like everything, it had an Achilles heel. Knock out the
rudder and it's like a big ship with nowhere to go.''
   Ballard's finding the Bismarck required almost as much
determination and luck as did Britain's sinking it. With sonar and
video and still cameras whirring away, Ballard spent two summers
combing a 100-square mile area of the ocean's bottom 600 miles west
of Brest, France.
   ``Ballard's cabin was a couple of doors down from us,'' said
Schnall, who accompanied the oceanographer on the search. ``And all
of sudden one morning, we hear this incredible scream because
Ballard has a video monitor in his room. He had just woken up and
he saw it: just as (the underwater camera) was crossing the
midsection of the ship, right across the gun turrets.
   ``And he let out a whoop. That woke me up, we ran down and
grabbed our camera just as he was running out the door. ... It was
one of those rare moments in film when you catch something exactly
as it happens.''
   What Ballard's cameras found more than 15,000 feet below the
surface of the Atlantic startled the team.
   ``It looked like the ship had just been launched from its
original berth,'' Schnall said. ``It sat straight up on its
bottom.''
   There were no skeletons or human bones in sight.
   ``The exciting thing (about making the documentary) is that it
is almost like a natural story,'' Schnall said. ``You have the
Bismarck going out, you have the Bismarck eluding the British, and
then eventually being sunk.
   ``And we have an explorer (Ballard) who goes to find the
Bismarck, can't find it, has to regroup himself, and then go back
out again the next year and find it.''
   After the filmmakers collected footage of the Bismarck's
wreckage, they met with some of the men who once served on her
decks and showed them the underwater footage.
   ``Very slowly, they started to say, `Yes. Isn't that the gun
where I was standing?' Or, `Wasn't that the deck where so-and-so
was standing before it went down?'
   ``And on and on it went. Eventually, they saw the swastika on
the stern of the ship. ... One of the survivors, Heinrich Kuhnt,
was asked what it felt like to have survived this horrible sea
battle. And he hesitated. And slowly tears filled his eyes and he
couldn't stop crying.''
</TEXT>
