<HEAD>Titanic Inquiry after 78 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inquiry will be held into the conduct of a
steamship captain who was criticized for not coming to the aid of
the Titanic when it sank 78 years ago, the government said Monday.
   The Titanic sank after striking an iceberg in the North Atlantic
on April 14, 1912. More than 1,500 of the 2,200 people aboard the
ship perished.
   The Marine Accident Investigation Branch will examine testimony
at the 1912 inquiry into the loss of the great liner to throw light
on the role of the late Capt. Stanley Lord, said a Department of
Transport spokeswoman.
   The inquiry comes in response to a campaign by Lord's relatives,
who have been trying to clear his name, said the spokeswoman. She
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The inquiry was first reported in Monday's editions of The Daily
Telegraph, which said a crucial piece of evidence would be the
position of the wreck as determined in 1985 by U.S. oceanographer
Robert Ballard.
   Lord was master of the Boston-bound Californian, believed to
have been the ship nearest to the Titanic when it struck the
iceberg.
   The Carpathia and other ships which were farther away than the
Californian did reach the scene in answer to the stricken liner's
distress calls.
   Lord's ship was stopped by ice at the time. The original inquiry
censured him for not responding to distress rockets from the
Titanic and ruled that as he was 8 to 10 miles from the liner he
could have gone to its aid and saved lives.
   Lord died in 1962, claiming to the end that the Titanic was in
an icefield 20 miles or more from his ship and that he was unable
to help. A campaign to clear his name has been carried on by his
son and other supporters, and an earlier petition to reopen the
inquiry was rejected in 1965.
   Lord insisted that a ship seen from the Californian was not the
Titanic. The ship was only identified in 1962 as the Samson, a
seal-hunter.
   ``Supporters of Capt. Lord claimed he was a scapegoat for the
failire of the Titanic's owners and the Board of Trade to make sure
there were enough lifeboats,'' The Daily Telegraph said.
   It quoted Capt. James de Coverley, deputy chief of marine
accidents, as saying the 1912 inquiry would not be reopened as that
had been into the Titanic's loss, not Lord's conduct.
   ``We are not in the business of rewriting history but in this
particular case it was considered desirable to have a
re-evaluation,'' de Coverley was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

