<HEAD>Titanic Discoverers To Hold Undersea `Classroom'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FALMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The undersea exploration of a Roman
shipwreck will be witnessed by thousands of students via
``telepresence,'' an on-the-spot TV broadcast brought to them by the
discoverers of the wreck of the Titanic.
   Plans for the unprecedented educational project were unveiled
Wednesday by Robert Ballard, who led the team that found the sunken
Titanic in 1985.
   Students linked by satellite to at least nine science museums in
the United States and Canada will be able to communicate with
explorers directing an unmanned mobile camera as it combs the floor
of the Mediterranean Sea, Ballard said.
   While the $6 million, privately funded project involves several
advances in technology, Ballard said its main purpose is to excite
students about science, a field that he said has suffered dwindling
influence in America.
   ``We really have a crisis of education in the United States,''
Ballard said at a news conference at the Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution. In recent years, he said, science has failed to provide
young people with attractive role models.
   The role models they have instead are ``that scientists are
nerds, or as my kids would say, dweebs, and dweebs sit at terminals
and are dropouts from society.''
   In the project, the underwater robot named Jason that helped
explore the Titanic will send high-quality television pictures via
cable to a ship thousands of feet above on the sea surface. For 14
days next May, the ship and its 50-member crew _ including six high
school students _ will control the movements of the robot and send
back satellite images from two underwater locations.
   The broadcasts will be transmitted via the Turner Broadcasting
System and Electronic Data Systems Corp. to science museums in
Boston, Chicago, Memphis, Tenn., Washington, D.C., Dallas,
Philadelphia, Rochester, N.Y., Charlotte, N.C., and Victoria,
British Columbia.
   In addition, the National Geographic Society plans to produce a
TV special on the expedition.
   The ship's crew will broadcast six programs a day, or a total of
84 40-minute programs, that will be seen by about 200,000 students.
   Instead of simply watching the programs, the students will have
before them a multiscreen ``control room'' that replicates the
control center on the mother ship above Jason. Students will be able
to ask questions of the crew, see images on a number of television
screens and, in some cases, even take over the controls of Jason,
Ballard said.
   Ballard called the concept ``telepresence.''
   The plan is for Jason to explore an undersea volcano field off
the west coast of Italy where minor eruptions, emissions of molten
minerals and an abundance of wildlife should be visible. At another
Mediterranean site, which Ballard declined to disclose, Jason will
photograph a vast debris field believed to be the remains of several
Roman shipwrecks from the second century.
   Ballard said the goals of the program, which he calls the ``Jason
Project,'' are both ambitious and basic. ``One of the major focuses
of the program is to teach people where the Mediterranean is,''
Ballard said.
   ``It's a tremendous interest-generator,'' said Frank Ireton of
the National Science Teachers Association, which is helping science
teachers who will take their classes to the programs.
   ``If we have 200,000 students and we interest 10 percent of them
in science, my gosh, that's a tremendous benefit,'' he said.
</TEXT>
