<LEADPARA>  Sea ice has set records on both sides of the world, with more in the Atlantic
and less in the Far East than ever recorded, government scientists said
Friday.;    Ice in the Atlantic reached 60 miles farther south than the record
set last April and was nearly to the region where an iceberg sank the Titanic
in 1912, the Navy-NOAA Joint Ice Center reported.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SEAS GROWING MORE ICE ON ONE SIDE OF EARTH  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     At the same time, sea ice reached a record minimum in the Sea of Okhotsk,
north of Japan, said Josh McDowell of NOAA.;    The Navy's and National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's center in Suitland, Md., tracks sea
ice as a warning service for shipping, seeking to prevent disasters like that
of the British liner Titanic.;    The maximum extent of the ice reached nearly
to the latitude of Boston -- though far to the east -- before pulling back
this week, officials said.;    Normally, sea ice reaches its maximum in April
in the North Atlantic. Cold weather could lead to an extension of the ice
edge, McDowell cautioned.;    Detailed information on the extent of sea ice
goes back only to 1972, when satellites began tracking frozen areas.;   
During that period, McDowell said, growth of ice on one side of the planet has
been accompanied by a decline on the other side.;    Sea ice is a sheet of
frozen salt water several inches thick along its edge, McDowell explained.
Temperatures have to be about 29 degrees Fahrenheit to freeze seawater.;   
While the sea ice could damage a ship that was not specially strengthened, it
was not the cause of the Titanic's demise. That ship fell victim to a floating
iceberg. Icebergs are large chunks of ice that break away from land and float
south.;    More than 1,500 people died when the Titanic struck the floating
mass of ice and sank April 14, 1912, on its first Atlantic crossing.  </TEXT>
