<HEAD>Underwater Explorer Will Help Children Explore Shipwrecks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underwater explorer Robert Ballard will guide
more than 250,000 children through a high-tech tour of two
shipwrecks from the War of 1812 in a science project sponsored by
the Jason Foundation for Education.
   About 40 children will accompany Ballard to Lake Ontario to
examine the remains of the Hamilton and Scourge, which Ballard
called ``incredible archeological treasures.'' More than a
quarter-million more students will view the expedition on screens
via satellite links in schools and museums across the United States
and Canada.
   The Jason Foundation, named for a robotic device used in the
explorations, last year went to the Mediterranean Sea to look at an
underground volcano and the deepest known ancient shipwreck site.
   Cameras will take the children on close-up tours of the lake and
sunken ships. They will be able to ask questions of Ballard during
the presentations and may also be permitted to operate the robot
through the satellite link, Ballard said.
   Ballard, senior scientist for the Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution in Massachusetts, discovered the Titanic in 1985 and
the German battleship Bismarck last year. He founded the Jason
Foundation for Education, a joint venture of educators, scientists,
museums and private industry, to encourage scientific careers among
American children.
   Ballard said there are no American graduate students at Woods
Hole, which is affiliated with MIT, and 60 percent of applicants
for the coming year are foreign. ``We are hopelessly behind France,
Germany, England and Japan,'' Ballard said. He said the problem
begins in grades 4-12 and results in widespread scientific
illiteracy.
   The Jason project will train more than 4,000 teachers in a
curriculum developed specifically for the Lake Ontario expedition.
Their pupils will be well-grounded in engineering, robotics, marine
biology, archeology, maritime history and other relevant areas by
the time Ballard and his crew begin broadcasting live from the lake
bottom on April 30.
   The next Jason project will take students to the Galapagos
Islands off the coast of Ecuador, Ballard said. The foundation may
also do a joint project in the South Pacific with Japan on the 50th
anniversary of Pearl Harbor in 1991, and may work with the
government of Spain on a 500th-anniversary commemoration of
Columbus' 1492 voyage to America.
</TEXT>
