<LEADPARA>  Egyptian authorities planned to resume their search today for survivors of a
ferry accident in which as many as 471 people were feared drowned in stormy
weather in the Red Sea.;   Waves tossed the ferry, which was carrying 649
workers and pilgrims returning from Saudi Arabia to Egypt, against a reef near
the small commercial Egyptian port of Safaga, sinking the boat in
shark-infested waters, officials said Sunday.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  471 FEARED DEAD AFTER FERRY SINKS IN RED SEA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     As many as 471 passengers were still missing Sunday night after a daylong
rescue effort that was hampered by high winds and 10-foot waves. Some were
believed to be possibly still stranded on lifeboats that drifted from the
rescue scene, where Australian and U.S. Navy helicopters briefly joined an
Egyptian armada plucking passengers and crew members from the sea.;   Egypt's
director of port security, Hassan al-Aghouri, said that by nightfall, rescuers
had picked up 178 survivors.;   Investigation ordered;   Egyptian Prime
Minister Atef Sidki and Interior Minister Abdel Halim Moussa traveled to the
site of the disaster in Safaga, about 60 miles south of the Red Sea tourist
resort city of Hurghada, and ordered an investigation into the cause of the
accident.;   The accident was probably the world's worst maritime disaster
since 1987, when a Philippines passenger ferry collided with an oil barge and
caught fire, leaving 4,386 people dead, and the second Red Sea shipping
accident this year. In April, 24 people died when an overloaded motor launch
sank about 60 miles north of Sunday's disaster site.;   Al-Aghouri identified
the ferry as the Egyptian-registered Salem Express owned by the Egyptian
Samatour Shipping Co., based in Alexandria. He said that the boat left
standard navigational channels and that investigators will question surviving
crew members about the change of course.;   Ship hit by 10 foot waves;   The
1,105-ton ship was sailing from Jidda, Saudi Arabia, to Safaga, a 36-hour
trip, when it was assaulted by 10-foot waves that were whipped by 40-mph
winds.;   The vessel rammed coral reefs about six miles off Safaga's harbor
about midnight Saturday and went down immediately, al-Aghouri said.;   He said
rescuers were unable to reach the area until dawn Sunday because of heavy
storms and high seas.;   Port official Islam Ahmed Zaki said high waves,
increasing winds, rain and darkness interrupted the search, which was to
resume early today.;   Authorities said they had pinpointed the location of
the sunken vessel about six miles off the coast of Egypt and would try to
raise it today.;   Some survivors criticized the crew for abandoning ship
without doing enough to help.;   One rescued passenger, agricultural engineer
Abdel-A'ati Hassan, said crew members told people to move to one side of the
listing ferry to keep it afloat, then abandoned ship.;   "They (crew members)
wore life preservers and left us and even pushed us aside to escape," Hassan
said from his bed at Safaga Central Hospital. "They left us with women and
kids, who died.";   The boat's first mate, Mahmoud Soleiman Rizake, said a
"terrible explosion" from the collision with the reef woke him in his cabin.; 
 "I got up and found that water was pouring in," he said in interviews with
the newspapers Al-Ahram and Algomhuria.;   He said he rushed to the deck to
help pump out the water, "but the ferry was swinging very strongly and losing
balance.";   "Waters flooded the ship in 10 minutes, causing it to sink," he
said, adding that he jumped overboard and swam until a rescue boat picked him
up.;   Red Sea full of sharks, reefs;   The Red Sea is noted for several
species of sharks, including the ferocious hammerhead. It also has some of the
world's greatest coral fields, treacherous for navigators.;   Egypt's deputy
director of port security, Brig. Abdel-Karim el-Gazzar, said that all but 10
of the 578 passengers were Egyptians, and that 292 were returning from
religious visits to Muslim holy places in Saudi Arabia.;   El-Gazzar said
foreign passengers included six Filipinos, two Malaysians, one Sudanese and
one Zaire national. A Sudanese also was among the 71-member crew, el-Gazzar
said.;   Cairo's state-owned radio quoted Samatour officials as saying that
the ship had veered off course in bad weather and that attempts had been made,
apparently unsuccessfully, to warn it.;   U.S. Navy officials in Bahrain said
warships on patrol in the Red Sea had not received a distress signal from the
stricken vessel, but they said that could mean either that the captain had not
used the normal emergency channel or that the ferry was outside the radio
range of ships patrolling in the region.  </TEXT>
