<DATELINE>SVALBARD, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet ocean liner carrying West German
tourists rammed an iceberg in the arctic Norwegian sea and was
taking on water Tuesday. Many of the more than 900 people aboard
abandoned ship, some onto ice floes.
   The 630-foot Maxim Gorky radioed north Norway's rescue central at
12:27 a.m. that it was listing after hitting an iceberg about 185
miles west of the Norwegian island of Svalbard, said a coast guard
spokesman.
   The Soviets and Norwegians said there were no reports of
injuries. Most of the passengers were West Germans, many of them
elderly.
   The ship, located east of northern Greenland, appeared stable but
was taking on water and Norwegian officials did not know if it would
sink, the Norwegian news agency NTB said.
   The Soviet news agency Tass said the crew had reduced the leak
``and the situation somewhat normalized ... The Maxim Gorky is
listing slightly.''
   The Norwegian coast guard vessel Senja reached the ship early
Tuesday and began rescuing 300 to 400 passengers from lifeboats and
from ice floes in near-freezing temperatures and light rain about
two miles from the Maxim Gorky. Some 225 people and the crew were
said to still be on board.
   ``The passengers appear to be in good shape and humor ... rescue
operations are somewhat difficult because the lifeboats are near the
ice, which is moving,'' said Senja captain Kjell Tveiten via the
ship's radio.
   About 575 passengers and 377 crew members were aboard the vessel,
the Soviet Merchant Marine Emergency Preparedness office told
Norwegian state radio. Tass put the total at 953.
   Tveiten said Maxim Gorky was listing to starboard and appeared
bow-heavy but did not seem to be in immediate danger of sinking.
   Some passengers had climbed onto thick ice floes to walk to
lifeboats and rafts lowered earlier from the damaged ship into the
near-freezing waters, reports said.
   The Norwegian Defense Command said six rescue helicopters were
dispatched and would begin carrying passengers to Svalbard, about a
two-hour flight.
   Several other Soviet and Norwegian ships were within 300 miles of
the distressed ship, which was in international waters.
   Hospitals in northern Norway and on the Norwegian islands of
Spitsbergen, of which Svalbard is the largest, were on emergency
alert.
   The Svalbard hospital was awaiting Norwegian medical teams
dispatched by helicopter, said reports.
   ``Maxim Gorky'' was built in West Germany in 1969 and was sold to
the Soviet Union in 1974.
   In recent summers, the liner has carried mostly West Germans on
tours from Hamburg arranged by German tour operator NUR, news
reports said.
