<DESCRIPT>  GREECE; BOAT; ACCIDENT; SOUTH-AFRICA; RESCUE; CONTROVERSY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Passengers from a Greek cruise ship that sank in stormy seas off South Africa
said today that the captain and crew abandoned the vessel while hundreds of
people were still on board.;    The ship's owner today defended the crew
against the accusations. The company said some crew members were the first to
board lifeboats as the liner Oceanos sank Sunday about a mile offshore. But
the company said they were needed to help the passengers aboard and assist
them onto rescue vessels.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CREW LEFT SINKING SHIP
4 MISSING, BUT ALL 361 PASSENGERS ARE SAFE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Last two paragraphs ran only in Street edition.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Capt. Yiannis Avranas also defended his decision to be among the first to
leave the ship, saying it was necessary to direct rescue operations from
shore.;    "I don't care what these people say about me. I am separated from
my family, who were rescued by one of the other ships, and I lost my own ship
-- what more do they want?" he asked.;    The South African air force said all
361 passengers were safe, but officials were still trying to determine the
fate of four missing crew members.;    More than 570 people were rescued by
military helicopters, cargo ships and other vessels Sunday, air force Maj.
Gerrie Evert said.;    Search operations were continuing; however, the missing
four may be on two ships that helped in the rescue but had not been contacted,
officials said. "We haven't seen any bodies in the water," Evert said.;   
Transport Ministry officials were investigating claims that many of the crew
were among the first to abandon the Durban-bound ship.;    Passengers claimed
crew members took the ship's only two motorized lifeboats, leaving passengers
to try to launch regular motorless lifeboats.;    "They left us in the lurch.
They knew . . . that the ship was going to sink and didn't say a thing," said
passenger Kevin Ellis. "All the crew who knew how to operate lifeboats had
gone.";    Stephanie Hankinson, the ship's photographer, said the crew's
departure created havoc: "They left, and there was a total state of panic
because nobody else knew how to let the lifeboats down.";    Employees and
entertainers of the South African tour company that rented the Oceanos
reportedly took over, launching lifeboats and helping people who were
airlifted to safety by helicopters.;    A spokesman for Epirotiki Lines, the
owner of the ship, said crew members played a critical role in the evacuation,
which he said went according to plan.;    "The fact that the operation was so
successful with all on board saved proves that the rescue plan was the correct
one," the spokesman, Capt. Alevizos Klaudatos, said in Athens.;    Terrified
passengers waited for help all night on the ship's upper deck. As the ship
began to list, some leaped overboard, Evert said.;    One man was rescued
after 10 hours in the water, eight miles from where the ship sank, said Air
Force Maj. Andres Steenkamp.;    The last people on board were rescued at
midday Sunday -- only 90 minutes before the Oceanos sank.;    Military
officials said they did not know why the ship began taking on water but that
its proximity to shore suggested it may have hit a reef off the dangerous
"Wild Coast.";    The captain said a piston in the engine room burst, knocking
a hole in the hull.;    The ship foundered when its engine room was flooded
and began listing heavily after it was battered by waves up to 24 feet high.; 
  Transport Minister P.J. Welgemoed said his department would investigate a
report that harbor officials in East London received a bomb threat about 24
hours before the vessel began taking on water.;    Police Maj. Gen. Johan Rust
said police went to the investigate but were denied access by Captain Avranas.
Rust said ship security officials reported finding no evidence of a bomb.;   
Ship officials denied Avranas would not allow authorities on board to search.;
   The 7,554-ton Oceanos -- 495 feet long and 64 feet wide -- was carrying
mostly South African passengers.;    In the rescue operation, military
helicopters airlifted more than 200 people off the ship, and 300 were pulled
from the sea or from life rafts. Planes dropped life preservers to people in
the water, and many people were saved by three merchant ships that rushed to
the scene.;    It had left the Indian Ocean port Saturday on the return leg of
a Durban-Cape Town-Durban cruise. It sank off Coffee Bay, part of the Transkei
black homeland.  </TEXT>
